year = {2022},
publisher = {IBM Corp.},
address = {USA},
abstract = {Earth’s population continues to grow and is expected to reach the United Nations’ projected 9.7 billion by 2050. Today, roughly 1/3 of people do not have access to safe drinking water and we are already experiencing the consequences of changing climate through increasing frequency and severity of droughts, floods and fires signal that weather is becoming more variable. An integrated solution with engagement from all basin stakeholders is vital to develop a means to acquire, analyze and visualize data to make smart decisions, arrive at ‘one version of the truth’ and educate the public. Our CASCON 2022 workshop began with concept background and rationale, followed by vignettes of major lessons learned over a four-year journey of platform development (platform technology, difficulties integrating pre-made solutions, Indigenous community engagement, sustainability of integrated components. Each vignette was followed by a question and answer period with the audience. We linked our technical research scope objectives and vignettes to workshop user outcomes; therefore, the audience took away insights into the collaborative process of working with a diverse stakeholder constituency, insights into IBM solutions and Alberta water management challenges, and the opportunity to engage with the platform in its development and release states.},
